==English==

===Etymology===
From Middle French ''[[sympathie]]'' < Late Latin [[sympathia]] < Greek [[συμπάθεια]] (''sympatheia'') "sympathy, affinity" < [[συμπαθής]] (''sympathēs'') "having a fellow feeling" < prefix [[συμ-]] (''[[sym-]]''), variant of [[συν-]] (''[[syn-]]'') "with, in company with, together with" + [[παθέω]] (''patheo'') "to have a secondary affection" < [[πάσχω]] (''pascho'') "to be affected by, to suffer" < Proto-Indo-European base ''*kwenth-'' ("to suffer," "to endure").

===Noun===
{{en-noun|sympath|ies}}

# A [[mutual]] [[relationship]] between [[people]] or [[thing]]s such that they are [[correspondingly]] [[affected]] by any [[external]] [[action]], [[force]], etc.
# The [[abilty]] to [[share]] the [[feeling]]s of another; [[empathy]].
# A feeling of [[pity]] or [[sorrow]] for the [[suffering]] or [[distress]] of another; [[compassion]].

